# Secure file I/O

When reading or writing sensitive data (credentials, tokens, keys, configs
with secrets), follow these patterns.

## Create files with restrictive permissions from the start

Never `File.write` then `File.chmod` — the file is briefly world-readable
between the two calls (TOCTOU race).

```ruby
# BAD: TOCTOU window between write and chmod
File.write(path, content)
File.chmod(0o600, path)

# GOOD: file is created with 0600 from the start
File.open(path, "w", 0o600) { |f| f.write(content) }

# GOOD: read-modify-write with creation mode
File.open(path, File::RDWR | File::CREAT, 0o600) do |f|
  # ...
end
```

## Correct permissions on pre-existing files and directories

`File.open`'s mode and `mkdir_p`'s mode only apply on **creation**. If the
file or directory already exists (created by a user, another tool, or an
older version of the code), the permissions are preserved.

Always `File.chmod` after write/mkdir as a belt-and-suspenders measure:

```ruby
FileUtils.mkdir_p(dir, mode: 0o700)
File.chmod(0o700, dir)  # corrects pre-existing directories

File.open(path, File::RDWR | File::CREAT, 0o600) { |f| ... }
File.chmod(0o600, path)  # corrects pre-existing files
```

## Use file locking for read-modify-write

Without locking, concurrent processes can clobber each other's writes.
Use `flock(LOCK_EX)` inside the `File.open` block:

```ruby
File.open(path, File::RDWR | File::CREAT, 0o600) do |f|
  f.flock(File::LOCK_EX)

  existing = f.read
  data = existing.empty? ? {} : parse(existing)
  data[key] = value

  f.rewind
  f.truncate(0)
  f.write(serialize(data))
end
```

The lock is released automatically when the block exits.

## Use safe deserialization

Never `YAML.load` or `YAML.load_file` on untrusted data — they allow
arbitrary object instantiation. Always use the safe variants:

```ruby
# BAD: arbitrary object instantiation
YAML.load_file(path)

# GOOD: only basic types (String, Hash, Array, Numeric, Boolean, nil)
YAML.safe_load_file(path)
YAML.safe_load(string)
```

## Suppress echo for secret input

When prompting for credentials, suppress terminal echo so the value
isn't visible on screen:

```ruby
require "io/console"

$stdout.print "Paste your token: "
value = $stdin.noecho { $stdin.gets.chomp }
$stdout.puts  # newline after hidden input
```

## Prefer multi-arg subprocess calls

When passing secrets to external commands, use multi-argument form to
avoid shell interpolation. Document any unavoidable CLI argument exposure:

```ruby
# BAD: shell interpolation — value could contain metacharacters
system("security add-generic-password -w #{value}")

# GOOD: multi-arg form, no shell
Kernel.system("security", "add-generic-password", "-w", value)
```

Note: CLI arguments are visible in `ps` output. Document this when the
external tool offers no stdin alternative.
